Cornell University

General information

  • Private not-for-profit, 4-year or above

  • Doctoral Universities: Very High Research Activity

  • Undergraduate enrollment is 15,043 (includes all undergrads; some of the numbers below are based on first time, full time, degree seeking students only).

  • See mission at https://www.cornell.edu/about/mission.cfm

  • 11% of applicants are admitted

  • 60% of admitted applicants choose to enroll

  • 97% of students stay after their first year

  • 95% of students graduate

  • The student to all faculty ratio is 9:1

  • The student to tenured or tenure-track faculty ratio is 47:1

  • Students are required to be vaccinated against COVID-19

  • Employees are required to be vaccinated against COVID-19

  • This college is located in a City: Small

  • The closest mass transit is a Inf minute walk away

  • For abortion access, as of July, 2022, the state this institution is in was ranked as having protective by the Guttmacher Institute, though this may change.

  • California does not consider this state to have anti-LGBTQ+ laws.

  • Athletic conference: Ivy Group

Diversity among the faculty

Two things to note here are diversity overall as well as the distribution tenure, tenure track, and non tenure track faculty. There are two main tracks in academia: faculty who are given short term contracts (and often a high teaching load and lower pay) and faculty who are essentially on probation (for 3-6 years, typically) and then are given tenure or fired. For more about tenure, see here. Tenure is a way of protecting academic freedom (tenured faculty can be fired for misconduct or if a program is closed, but not for their research or speech); the fact that it is often more stable also helps ensure that faculty will be at an institution long term to serve as mentors, letter writers, etc. Having more non-tenure-track faculty can save money (they are often paid less, and teach more), reduce public dissent (they can be fired for taking a stand unpopular with their employer), and reduce research or other creative output, including mentoring in these areas (teaching loads are often higher, and research/creative output expectations lower, for faculty in non-tenure-track positions at large universities).
